New class org.junit.Assert already contains optimized assert methods (with Long.valueOf etc), for example:
```java
    static public void assertEquals(String message, long expected, long actual) {
        if (expected != actual) {
            failNotEquals(message, Long.valueOf(expected), Long.valueOf(actual));
        }
    }
```

Old (deprecated) version of this class (junit.framework.Assert) contains not-optimized methods, for example:
```java
    static public void assertEquals(String message, long expected, long actual) {
        assertEquals(message, new Long(expected), new Long(actual));
    }
```

Whole class is deprecated, but I sure that this methods are still used in many projects, so I suggest to optimize them, until they are presented in JUnit.

```java
@Override
public boolean equals(Object obj) {
    return toString().equals(obj.toString());
}
```

Problems:
* As you can see the old version of "equals" method could throw NullPointerException (obj.toSting()). 
* And also it has not got check for correct class (instanceOf).

It will be better to make additional check: obj instanceof ParameterizedAssertionError

Hello,
I am still learning JUnit so I may be having weird ideas, but I don't understand why something like this isn't available.

I've read that the 'standard' way to check that a method is throwing an exception is to add the 'expected' tag to the Test annotation. 
But I see two problems with that:
- You can't tell exactly which line in the test method is supposed to throw the exception
- If you are testing different way to throw one specific exception, you won't be able to tell if it has been throws everytime as expected. And you will have to create several methods to test for the same exception.
I find it confusing in a general way because the test corresponds to the method and not to an actual part of the program we're trying to test.

I think the exceptions should be checked using a method. Here's what I have in mind:

assertThrows(TestException.class, new Testable() {
    @Override
    public void test() {
        // Call tested method here
    });

Here TestException is the exception class we're expecting the method to throw. 
assertThrows calls test(), tries to catch a Throwable, and checks if it is of type TestException, or a subtype of TestException. If no exception is caught, or if the exception is not of the expected type, the test fails.

Is it possible to have something like this?

